1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:21,600
 I can look up anything, anytime, anyplace. I have information with me everywhere. But how does that all fit together? How do I bring these truths together? And how do those truths actually speak to my life? Like, what do they have to say about how I raise my children? What do they say about how I treat other people at work?

2
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:45,200
 I think Catholicism gives people the possibility of doing that. And I think that it's an exciting opportunity for Catholic AI to engage with those questions and let people have fun, let people challenge the system, let people ask, and kind of enter into this updated version of the scholastic university, where you'd have the disputed questions, where you'd have the back and forth.

3
00:00:45,200 --> 00:01:02,200
 This is an opportunity to kind of bring that reality and that harmonization of different disciplines that existed in the great universities of the past. Maybe we can bring that reality to every phone, every computer in the world. And that's exciting.

4
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:24,200
 Hello, and welcome to the Catholic Futurist Podcast. My name is Benjamin Crockett, and I'm your host. We look at the world of tomorrow, the merging technologies, and we look at those forks, and we bring in the moral and intellectual tradition of the church. And today is my great honor and my great pleasure to be speaking with Fr. Michael Baggett here in Rome.

5
00:01:24,200 --> 00:01:25,200
 Hi, Ben. Great to be here.

6
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:33,200
 It is fantastic to be here with you, Fr. Michael. And we're in our new studio here on the day after Pope Leo XIV has been announced.

7
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:38,200
 Very exciting. Yeah, we were both there for the announcement, and we were a bit surprised.

8
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:49,200
 Yeah, no, I mean, it's just absolutely exciting and incredible. And speaking of that, the exciting and incredible news is the world of AI that keeps marching faster and faster forward.

9
00:01:49,200 --> 00:02:02,200
 And, Father, one of our big projects here at Longbeard and with the Catholic Futurist Podcast is to look at AI and to try to bring in those Catholic values, those Catholic themes, and to embed it into this new technology.

10
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:09,200
 But, Father, while we're doing that, why is Catholic AI important? Why is it important for the church to be involved?

11
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:24,200
 Well, AI is shaping practically every dimension of life. We can look at the workforce, education, medicine, warfare, relationships in the family, among friends, practically every aspect of life.

12
00:02:24,200 --> 00:02:36,200
 So we, as a church, as an expert in humanity, want to make sure we're giving the right guidance and make sure that these great values are informing and shaping the design of AI systems.

13
00:02:36,200 --> 00:02:46,200
 So I think the Catholic AI comes primarily in that aspect of promoting the right values and making sure that these different systems are well designed.

14
00:02:46,200 --> 00:02:52,200
 And we live in an age of confusion. We live in an age sometimes of deception, of manipulation.

15
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:58,200
 And so we want to make sure that we're sharing the truth. These systems are promoting the truth and are reliable.

16
00:02:58,200 --> 00:03:07,200
 And that different users have a certain confidence that they are gaining the right guidance, the right responses.

17
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:15,200
 We may never reach that perfectly, but we at least can do our best to design them to move in that direction.

18
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:32,200
 And Father, when you're speaking with people who are working actively in artificial intelligence, do you find that a good majority of them have values that we could align and say that they are Catholic or the majority of them, you know, kind of floating around in that secular space and not thinking in terms of those traditional Catholic values?

19
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:36,200
 Well, I think that there is a deep fundamental human desire for truth.

20
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:45,200
 You know, St. Augustine, a long time ago, said that all of us, many people may deceive, but no one wants to be deceived.

21
00:03:45,200 --> 00:04:05,200
 So I think there is this fundamental desire for truth. And unfortunately, there are also some temptations to let that value become a little secondary to economic expediency, to ease of use, to a notion of engagement in which the particular user is just so compelled to stay on the platform.

22
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:26,200
 We've seen this recently with some problems in the rather sycophantic design in major large language model design, where people are told that they are absolute geniuses, even when they quite deliberately put in rather dumb prompts to test the system.

23
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:36,200
 They're told that they basically are brilliant and misunderstood and that they need to keep going forward in their creative expression.

24
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:41,200
 So there's that temptation to flatter users, if you will, to kind of deepen that engagement.

25
00:04:41,200 --> 00:04:46,200
 And that's where we start to see this fundamental longing for truth set to the wayside.

26
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:58,200
 And Father, when you look at, you know, the challenges that AI poses and also the challenges that we have in building, you know, AI with these values, what do you think are the challenges that are most worth tackling for the church within AI?

27
00:04:58,200 --> 00:04:59,200
 Yeah, that's a great question.

28
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:10,200
 I think that we need the humility to recognize that there are a lot of complicated questions out there, philosophical questions, moral questions.

29
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:18,200
 And so there can be a temptation sometimes to just sort of promote a narrow political ideology or some other narrow view.

30
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:26,200
 So we want to make sure that people are coming to different systems are really getting information, getting the tools they need to do an authentic discernment.

31
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:43,200
 Because while well-designed AI systems can be tremendously illuminating, can be informative, can summarize large bodies of data that would take us many hours, days, years sometimes to reflect upon.

32
00:05:43,200 --> 00:05:51,200
 They can never replace the very human decision making process and that moral responsibility.

33
00:05:51,200 --> 00:06:02,200
 Because ultimately we're going to be responsible as human agents for decisions that are made in our personal life, but also decisions that are made in the criminal justice system, for instance.

34
00:06:02,200 --> 00:06:10,200
 So these design issues have very widespread societal impact as well.

35
00:06:10,200 --> 00:06:13,200
 And we don't want to outsource what is most human.

36
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:20,200
 We want to enhance our capacities to understand situations, to assess them better, and to make responsible decisions.

37
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:26,200
 And Father, you mentioned, you know, kind of that moral worth that humans have and that ability for us to make moral judgments.

38
00:06:26,200 --> 00:06:39,200
 There was a recent, I think it was a research paper that was provided by Anthropic where they talked about the moral status of these AI systems and the potential, you know, as things continue to progress, what do we do with that?

39
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:42,200
 What does the church make of those claims?

40
00:06:42,200 --> 00:06:48,200
 Well, there is something very unique about the human being.

41
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:57,200
 We see the human being as having these capacities for intellectual insight, these capacities for free decisions.

42
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:07,200
 And so these AI systems might be able to emulate and mimic some of the expressions of those human characteristics, but we don't want to blur the lines here.

43
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:13,200
 We want to keep in mind the clear differences between human beings and the different products, artifacts that they design.

44
00:07:13,200 --> 00:07:26,200
 We want to make sure that these AI systems remain as tools, tools to improve, to illumine, to aid and assist those unique human characteristics, those unique capacities.

45
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:36,200
 What we don't want to do is try to imagine some sort of new, superior digital person, if you will.

46
00:07:36,200 --> 00:07:44,200
 And we don't want to confuse what is mimicked and systems that emulate these characteristics with actual persons.

47
00:07:44,200 --> 00:07:51,200
 So I would be very uncomfortable to start attributing a kind of moral status to the actual systems.

48
00:07:51,200 --> 00:08:00,200
 I'm certainly concerned about the moral implications of the human decisions that are made in design and development of the systems.

49
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:07,200
 But I wouldn't want to absolve the human beings of their responsibility for the decisions that are made.

50
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:14,200
 And I want to keep that distinction between the human and the machine quite clear as we go along.

51
00:08:14,200 --> 00:08:33,200
 And that makes me think, Father, of one of the topics that's dear to your heart, which is looking at that blurring within artificial intimacy and how these systems will take up more and more space in people's lives as loneliness, as technology kind of moves into these spaces and takes up more and more of our time.

52
00:08:33,200 --> 00:08:48,200
 Sure, because as the systems get better and better about guiding us or suggesting information, the temptation sets in to think of them as more reliable, more available, more supportive of us than real life human beings.

53
00:08:48,200 --> 00:08:59,200
 But one of the beauties about human interpersonal relationships is that good friends, good family members sometimes challenge us, sometimes correct us.

54
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:05,200
 And they also can exercise an empathy that these systems will always lack.

55
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:12,200
 So there's always going to be a kind of asymmetry between humans and the machines that they use.

56
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:17,200
 Like we'll be able to find a lot of benefit, even guidance from them.

57
00:09:17,200 --> 00:09:23,200
 But there's not that same interpersonal exchange of love, of care, of sympathy and compassion, right?

58
00:09:23,200 --> 00:09:27,200
 Because they can't really empathize with us without an emotional life.

59
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:29,200
 They can't suffer with us.

60
00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:32,200
 They can't have that true, authentic compassion.

61
00:09:32,200 --> 00:09:49,200
 So as helpful as they may be as tools, they're not going to or ought not to replace these other really enriching relationships in our lives, which again, can be uncomfortable, can be very hard to develop, can be hard to sustain, but are some of the richest experiences of our life.

62
00:09:49,200 --> 00:10:06,200
 Now, I'm very open to the possibility that some of the AI systems can provide some aid, especially people who struggle for a particular reason, maybe because of trauma, maybe because they're neurologically divergent, or they're going through a difficult time, or they're in a new social situation.

63
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:12,200
 I'm open to getting some initial training in the social life through these systems, a kind of social simulator.

64
00:10:12,200 --> 00:10:23,200
 But I think that that social simulation ought always to be geared to a better and richer real life, real world, interpersonal experience with other human beings.

65
00:10:23,200 --> 00:10:29,200
 So if we have that goal in mind, then they can assist along the way, but they should aid, not replace.

66
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:37,200
 And Father, I want to touch back on something that you'd mentioned about kind of that blurring of the line with AI and with these technologies.

67
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:45,200
 Something that I find kind of worrisome, I mean, there is an aspect where I am inspired, because I think that innovation is a beautiful thing.

68
00:10:45,200 --> 00:10:54,200
 And I think that innovation, kind of that mission of the individual to be led by their curiosity, to continue to develop, to make their circumstances better.

69
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:55,200
 I think that's incredible.

70
00:10:55,200 --> 00:10:58,200
 And I'm a huge believer in curiosity and creativity.

71
00:10:58,200 --> 00:11:11,200
 Something that I find uniquely challenging and worrisome, though, about the AI space in particular, is that that technology, not only is it kind of developing at a speed that for the average person is almost impossible to keep up with.

72
00:11:11,200 --> 00:11:27,200
 But another thing is that it allows for people's weaknesses and negative characteristics and qualities to be exaggerated to such a proportion that I feel like, okay, I'm an adult, I have children, I have a lot of things that keep me in the real world.

73
00:11:27,200 --> 00:11:47,200
 But if someone has not built in the habits to really learn and spend time learning or has not developed the courage or that personal will to, you know, live in the real world and to meet someone and to, you know, pursue that person and to develop themselves in a way where you're attractive to other people and you bring good people together.

74
00:11:47,200 --> 00:11:50,200
 So AI seems to be accelerating that.

75
00:11:50,200 --> 00:11:59,200
 And one of the subjects that I know that you're passionate about and you're studying actively is that area of artificial intimacy, that area of artificial companionship.

76
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:04,200
 And this is all stuff that seemed just a few years ago to be something that was relatively science fiction-esque.

77
00:12:04,200 --> 00:12:05,200
 Sure.

78
00:12:05,200 --> 00:12:17,200
 How is the church encouraging young people to, you know, actually live in the real world and pursue relationships that are meaningful and can be challenging and can be hurtful and all those things, but that within that pain we grow?

79
00:12:17,200 --> 00:12:20,200
 How is the church engaging in that space?

80
00:12:20,200 --> 00:12:30,200
 And, you know, not just with artificial intimacy, but also within that whole gamified universe where people can find real meaning, real value, real development, but it's all official.

81
00:12:30,200 --> 00:12:47,200
 And I'm not saying there's not, I'm not saying that there's not value in team building those team qualities and getting better at something, but if you're just ameliorating the digital circumstances that's providing you satisfaction, but is not actually making you heroic in that real sense.

82
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:49,200
 How, how, how do you think about that?

83
00:12:49,200 --> 00:12:55,200
 And how do you, how are you actively engaging to, to, to bring the church's message into that space?

84
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:57,200
 Yeah, that's a great question.

85
00:12:57,200 --> 00:13:17,200
 As a Catholic educator, as a professor, I'm constantly thinking about how I can help my students form the human, emotional, and social skills that the church has always promoted, but that in a sense are more valuable than ever, because so much is being automated and so much more will be automated.

86
00:13:17,200 --> 00:13:32,200
 So if my focus is primarily on distributing a set of information, then I'm failing them, because they can thankfully get a lot of that information already, and it will only be more accessible to them in the future, which is generally a good thing.

87
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:41,200
 But that increase in information is no guarantee for an increase in discernment, an increase in prudence or an increase in wisdom.

88
00:13:41,200 --> 00:13:47,200
 So I need to help them form those skills, which are going to come through lots of different paths, right?

89
00:13:47,200 --> 00:14:02,200
 I think the church has been very good in helping to develop the university system, in the scholastic debates that people like Thomas Aquinas had.

90
00:14:02,200 --> 00:14:16,200
 That's such an amazing structure for us today, where you go and you listen and study attentively all the different worldviews that are out there, all the philosophies, all the religions, and you search out any elements of truth that can be found there.

91
00:14:16,200 --> 00:14:22,200
 And you see how you can bring those elements together into a unified worldview, into a unified picture.

92
00:14:22,200 --> 00:14:31,200
 And you do that sometimes in a clash of views with debate that's respectful, but that's serious.

93
00:14:31,200 --> 00:14:48,200
 So I really enjoy bringing my students into those conversations, to have a sympathetic look at worldviews that are not their own, and then have them enter into formal debate or critical conversations, where they're able to explore the nuances on perspectives.

94
00:14:48,200 --> 00:14:56,200
 And where they're able to really assimilate more deeply their own convictions and see how those beautiful ideas actually impact their life, right?

95
00:14:56,200 --> 00:15:09,200
 Because their time of formal education will end, but the different habits, the virtues that they form, intellectual virtues, moral virtues, that's what's really going to drive them forward in the future.

96
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:17,200
 So I think the church is really well equipped with her patrimony of wisdom and her longstanding commitment to education.

97
00:15:17,200 --> 00:15:21,200
 So we should really be on the forefront of this.

98
00:15:21,200 --> 00:15:27,200
 We should continue to be leaders in this area to make sure that we're forming those virtues that are transferable, right?

99
00:15:27,200 --> 00:15:30,200
 They're not going to go out of date.

100
00:15:30,200 --> 00:15:34,200
 They don't have an expiration date just because of a new technological development.

101
00:15:34,200 --> 00:15:40,200
 They're actually something that can bring with them to different social settings, to new situations.

102
00:15:40,200 --> 00:15:45,200
 And so that's one area where I think the church can do a lot, that educational system.

103
00:15:45,200 --> 00:16:09,200
 And of course, the responsibility of education also falls to parents, to be able to assist their children and to help families develop in that little school of virtue, the domestic church, where you're constantly, and you know full well, as a father, as a husband, you're called day in and day out to new forms of self-sacrifice you probably didn't even know existed.

104
00:16:09,200 --> 00:16:10,200
 There's no off switch.

105
00:16:10,200 --> 00:16:11,200
 No, no, no.

106
00:16:11,200 --> 00:16:22,200
 And Father, as AI continues to progress, we know from our listeners, from our conversations, from people that we've just been in daily contact with, that there is some anxiety.

107
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:34,200
 There's stress about what's work going to look like, what's society going to look like, what are the economics and political circumstances, how are they going to be transformed by this technology?

108
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:45,200
 Can you help our audience paint a picture of what does a good future look like, where AI is developed, is mature, is being used in all the ways that we hope it can be used for?

109
00:16:45,200 --> 00:16:46,200
 And how do we get there?

110
00:16:46,200 --> 00:16:54,200
 Oh, I bet every world leader would like to know this answer, right?

111
00:16:54,200 --> 00:17:00,200
 Well, I think that we can take the right steps if we're developing those virtues that I alluded to earlier.

112
00:17:00,200 --> 00:17:23,200
 If we help people recognize the value of work as a path of human growth, as a path of collaboration, no matter how small that work may seem or how big it may be on the world stage, there's a sense that there should be an intrinsic goodness, a formative value to your work.

113
00:17:23,200 --> 00:17:30,200
 That it's a place where you're using your unique talent at the service of others.

114
00:17:30,200 --> 00:17:42,200
 I was reading an author recently who was heavily involved in a business school, and he said, "Human excellence is often achieved when we take our competency and we put it at the service of others."

115
00:17:42,200 --> 00:17:43,200
 So I think that's what we want to look for.

116
00:17:43,200 --> 00:18:00,200
 Whether you're doing coding, whether you're painting buildings, whether you're designing cars, whether you're writing books, you want to take your gifts and achieve a competency in that field and put that competency at the service of others.

117
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:05,200
 That interpersonal exchange where we really recognize our need for one another.

118
00:18:05,200 --> 00:18:14,200
 I think if we can achieve that exchange and we find value in the work, whatever it may be, then we can go forward with a sense of meaning and purpose.

119
00:18:14,200 --> 00:18:17,200
 Yeah, but Father, if I can just push back for one second.

120
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:38,200
 I 100% agree with that, but there have been people in very high places in the political and economic sphere where they're talking about, and I don't know, obviously no one knows how soon this will happen, but they're talking about like 40% unemployment by 2030, whether it's because of transportation, whether it's because of automation, whether it's white collar, blue collar.

121
00:18:38,200 --> 00:18:47,200
 And I 100% agree that work is meaning, work is dignity, work is beyond just the economic value and how much you're contributing in that sense.

122
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:58,200
 But when we're in a place, which seems at least not too far away, where there's a huge percentage of that population that actually cannot add any positive economic value.

123
00:18:58,200 --> 00:19:03,200
 They are not able to, and that's a very scary place.

124
00:19:03,200 --> 00:19:14,200
 If we don't get that right, and I believe, and we all believe here, that if the church is not at the center of that, people can be very angry, people can be very desperate, and that can be a very dark and scary place.

125
00:19:14,200 --> 00:19:15,200
 Right.

126
00:19:15,200 --> 00:19:26,200
 How do we get past that, or how do we at least paint a picture and arrive at a place where it's okay?

127
00:19:26,200 --> 00:19:29,200
 Yeah, that's a challenging question.

128
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:36,200
 I was thinking of the fact that the new pope chose the name Leo XIV, and of course he's evoking his predecessor, Leo XIII.

129
00:19:36,200 --> 00:19:43,200
 And one of Leo XIII's major contributions was developing this contemporary notion of Catholic social teaching.

130
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:44,200
 Mm-hmm.

131
00:19:44,200 --> 00:19:46,200
 And Leo XIII saw the new things.

132
00:19:46,200 --> 00:19:53,200
 The new things were heavily tied to technological developments and the human implications of those technological developments.

133
00:19:53,200 --> 00:20:12,200
 And he placed the attention of the church squarely on worker dignity, worker rights, and finding the best ways to organize them so that those who weren't really appearing to contribute much to society were not just set aside and thrown aside as useless.

134
00:20:12,200 --> 00:20:41,200
 So I think that one of the many challenges of this pontificate, together with all of his advisors and everyone else who has insights on this issue, is to really develop a kind of new, deepened appreciation for the dignity of each human person and create the proper social structures so that those who are not able to pivot quickly in this huge economic disruption are not just forgotten and left behind.

135
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:56,200
 That there's some sort of safety net there and assistance in education so that they can transition to a way of actually using their time and talents in a valuable, worthwhile way and not forgotten and set aside.

136
00:20:56,200 --> 00:21:06,200
 But that's going to be a major, major challenge and commitment on the part of the church in collaboration with all the other people in the world who are thinking seriously about this.

137
00:21:06,200 --> 00:21:13,200
 And then Father, I guess my final question would be, where do you think we're going to be in a few years with Catholic AI? What are your hopes with Catholic AI?

138
00:21:13,200 --> 00:21:34,200
 Well, I want to see Catholic AI as a reality that is readily acknowledged and accessible, not only to Catholics, but to those outside the church. So I want reliable responses to those questions of mere curiosity.

139
00:21:34,200 --> 00:21:41,200
 We just lived through a conclave where the entire world is spending hours each day waiting for white smoke to come out of a chimney.

140
00:21:41,200 --> 00:21:48,200
 There's clearly this curiosity, this interest that people have in the institution of the church.

141
00:21:48,200 --> 00:22:06,200
 And so I want all of those people in those moments of grace where they might just have an interesting question about the church to have ready access to reliable information that they can then reflect upon and bring up with real life Catholics and practicing Catholics.

142
00:22:06,200 --> 00:22:16,200
 But I think that Catholic AI should be an easy entry point for people who have those questions, concerns, confusions, maybe even objections to the faith.

143
00:22:16,200 --> 00:22:20,200
 And so I want to see this as being something that's widespread, readily accessible.

144
00:22:20,200 --> 00:22:34,200
 And then I also want to see Catholic values instilled in how we use AI and all those other fields we mentioned earlier, right, so that the health care system is taking advantage of developments in drug discovery and drug testing and drug development.

145
00:22:34,200 --> 00:22:40,200
 We're making breakthroughs, we're making breakthroughs, for instance, in the treatment of Alzheimer's and dementia.

146
00:22:40,200 --> 00:22:47,200
 We're really putting these tools at the service of the weak, the frail, the vulnerable, the forgotten.

147
00:22:47,200 --> 00:22:50,200
 I want to see that becoming more widespread.

148
00:22:50,200 --> 00:23:06,200
 And I want us to kind of shift away from just thinking of these as nice, interesting, sometimes scary tools of a few people who happen to be technologically inclined to just really being inbuilt, integrated into what we consider most important in life.

149
00:23:06,200 --> 00:23:21,200
 Yeah, and Father, I think my personal opinion is that as the values that are building the majority of these AI systems, and we've talked a lot off air about transhumanism and about these different value systems that aren't grounded in something that is really truly faithful.

150
00:23:21,200 --> 00:23:32,200
 I think that Catholic AI is going to take a larger and larger space because people are going to want to have, you know, something that's documented, that's doctrinal, that has that authority and that clarity that the church can provide.

151
00:23:32,200 --> 00:23:41,200
 Why do you think, what do you think are the biggest challenges for us to get there, though, where more people start to want to be participating in Catholic AI?

152
00:23:41,200 --> 00:23:46,200
 Well, there can be a fear that Catholic AI is something that's sectarian.

153
00:23:46,200 --> 00:23:52,200
 It's just one particular group, and there are lots of value systems and lots of different perspectives on how to organize your life.

154
00:23:52,200 --> 00:23:57,200
 So why pay attention to Catholicism as opposed to other systems?

155
00:23:57,200 --> 00:24:04,200
 And so I get that. That's the perennial challenge of pluralism, right? And I think that's going to be with us for a while.

156
00:24:04,200 --> 00:24:11,200
 One of the things that I think is very exciting about Catholic AI in that regard is that people are starting to discover how rich and nuanced the Catholic tradition is.

157
00:24:11,200 --> 00:24:23,200
 And they're starting to discover that these aren't just a set of fairytale ideas that have been imposed from one generation to another, that there's actually a lot of serious thought, reflection and debate.

158
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:28,200
 So people are starting to find out about Thomas Aquinas, about St. August.

159
00:24:28,200 --> 00:24:35,200
 And they say, well, wait a second. These really brilliant people actually wrestled with the kind of issues that I have today.

160
00:24:35,200 --> 00:24:42,200
 And this Catholic system is not so narrow or close to other elements.

161
00:24:42,200 --> 00:24:58,200
 So I think that this is actually a key moment for us to expose more people to that richness and that nuance and give them that space to wrestle with the deep questions, to prompt, to go deeper, to find better arguments, better resources.

162
00:24:58,200 --> 00:25:18,200
 And we ought to have a healthy confidence that this is not just a narrow-minded sectarian system and not just one among many, but that there's space to integrate whatever's true, good, and beautiful in all these different philosophies or ways of thinking into kind of a coherent whole.

163
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:28,200
 And I think that that's an attractive selling point to Catholicism in general, but Catholic AI in particular, because we feel the weight of fragmentation.

164
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:32,200
 I can look up anything, any time, any place.

165
00:25:32,200 --> 00:25:35,200
 I have information with me everywhere.

166
00:25:35,200 --> 00:25:38,200
 But how does that all fit together?

167
00:25:38,200 --> 00:25:40,200
 How do I bring these truths together?

168
00:25:40,200 --> 00:25:43,200
 And how do those truths actually speak to my life?

169
00:25:43,200 --> 00:25:46,200
 Like, what do they have to say about how I raise my children?

170
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:49,200
 What do they say about how I treat other people at work?

171
00:25:49,200 --> 00:25:53,200
 Catholicism gives people the possibility of doing that.

172
00:25:53,200 --> 00:26:12,200
 And I think that that's an exciting opportunity for Catholic AI to engage with those questions and let people have fun, let people challenge the system, let people ask, and kind of enter into this updated version of the Scholastic University, where you'd have the disputed questions, where you'd have

173
00:26:12,200 --> 00:26:14,200
 You'd have the back and forth.

174
00:26:14,200 --> 00:26:25,200
 It's an opportunity to kind of bring that reality and that harmonization of different disciplines that existed in the great universities of the past.

175
00:26:25,200 --> 00:26:29,200
 Maybe we can bring that reality to every phone, every computer in the world.

176
00:26:29,200 --> 00:26:30,200
 And that's exciting.

177
00:26:30,200 --> 00:26:39,200
 And Father, that's, I mean, that's so exciting that, you know, AI and particularly Catholic AI can provide that nuance, can provide that information, that context, that history.

178
00:26:39,200 --> 00:26:43,200
 Those are things that I actually actively use every day on Magisterium AI.

179
00:26:43,200 --> 00:26:48,200
 But Father, what are the specific areas where AI should not go and cannot go?

180
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:51,200
 Well, we talked a lot about that intimacy, right?

181
00:26:51,200 --> 00:26:55,200
 So there is no AI system that can replace human friendship.

182
00:26:55,200 --> 00:27:01,200
 And there's no AI system that's going to be able to take away the value, for instance, of a good spiritual director.

183
00:27:01,200 --> 00:27:03,200
 Because a good spiritual director doesn't just give you information.

184
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:07,200
 The good spiritual director accompanies you on this journey of growth.

185
00:27:07,200 --> 00:27:23,200
 And so some applications can give you sound advice, but you need that living person, that guide to really show you how to apply that more concretely to your state, to your challenges, to your reality.

186
00:27:23,200 --> 00:27:32,200
 So I would never want to lose that unique role of authentic companionship and friendship, that unique role of the spiritual director.

187
00:27:32,200 --> 00:27:37,200
 And then we get to, of course, the sacraments, which I think about often as a priest, right?

188
00:27:37,200 --> 00:27:44,200
 I have full job security in that sense, because no AI system is ever going to be able to administer the sacraments.

189
00:27:44,200 --> 00:27:48,200
 This speaks to the incarnational logic of the church, right?

190
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:57,200
 We believe in a God who became man, who took on human flesh, and who interacts with fleshy beings, human beings, through visible signs.

191
00:27:57,200 --> 00:28:06,200
 And so he continues his ministry in a very physical, grounded, rooted, and communal reality of the church.

192
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:21,200
 So no matter how many brilliant insights you're able to find in AI systems, thanks be to God, there's no replacing the sacramental system that lived here and now experience of the divine, of the eternal.

193
00:28:21,200 --> 00:28:25,200
 And it's not just a private, you know, me and Jesus experience.

194
00:28:25,200 --> 00:28:27,200
 It's always a communal experience.

195
00:28:27,200 --> 00:28:30,200
 We're baptized, surrounded by our loved ones.

196
00:28:30,200 --> 00:28:35,200
 We're married in the presence of a community, right?

197
00:28:35,200 --> 00:28:42,200
 We celebrate the Eucharist together as a people of God on a journey, on a pilgrimage toward heaven together.

198
00:28:42,200 --> 00:28:53,200
 So in a world where we can often feel isolated and even absorbed by really attractive digital devices, the church says, wait, there's more.

199
00:28:53,200 --> 00:28:57,200
 There's the embodied experience and there's the communal experience.

200
00:28:57,200 --> 00:29:07,200
 And I think that what things like Magisterium AI do so well is the window, the opening to the curious or to those who just want to go deeper.

201
00:29:07,200 --> 00:29:11,200
 And then from there, you're directed into that communal experience.

202
00:29:11,200 --> 00:29:14,200
 You're directed into a church community.

203
00:29:14,200 --> 00:29:19,200
 You're directed into a one-on-one conversation with a trusted spiritual guide.

204
00:29:19,200 --> 00:29:21,200
 I think there should be that collaboration.

205
00:29:21,200 --> 00:29:24,200
 It's not always easy to see how to best make that transition.

206
00:29:24,200 --> 00:29:29,200
 So that's something I think we're continuing to think a lot about, but that's definitely the goal.

207
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:39,200
 This may be the starting point for some growth, but you're really going to flourish in the community with other believers.

208
00:29:39,200 --> 00:29:43,200
 And Father, what do you say to someone who's like, well, I live in a very isolated region.

209
00:29:43,200 --> 00:29:46,200
 There are no priests or there's very few priests.

210
00:29:46,200 --> 00:29:48,200
 There's, you know, this robot priest that comes in.

211
00:29:48,200 --> 00:29:50,200
 And by the way, he's more accurate.

212
00:29:50,200 --> 00:29:52,200
 He gets his theology 100%.

213
00:29:52,200 --> 00:29:55,200
 I feel comfortable because of whatever.

214
00:29:55,200 --> 00:29:58,200
 How do we push back on that where, you know, there's also the temptation.

215
00:29:58,200 --> 00:30:01,200
 I remember during COVID where I want to live stream mass.

216
00:30:01,200 --> 00:30:04,200
 I don't want to get up and go to mass because it's too far.

217
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:05,200
 It's complicated.

218
00:30:05,200 --> 00:30:10,200
 You know, it feels like technology can also in many respects get in the way in that sense.

219
00:30:10,200 --> 00:30:11,200
 Yeah.

220
00:30:11,200 --> 00:30:14,200
 So let's leverage the benefits there.

221
00:30:14,200 --> 00:30:19,200
 Let's gain all of the great insight from a well-trained system and the information.

222
00:30:19,200 --> 00:30:27,200
 But there's something indispensable and unique about that embodied experience, the communal experience.

223
00:30:27,200 --> 00:30:35,200
 As I said, in the sacramental system, it's God himself and his church has willed to transmit invisible grace through visible forms.

224
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:42,200
 So I think we can be very confident that we're gaining and we're growing in something in a very unique way.

225
00:30:42,200 --> 00:30:46,200
 So that's at the highest supernatural level, right?

226
00:30:46,200 --> 00:30:54,200
 In the level of faith that God has chosen to transmit these invisible graces to us in a concrete, visible manner in a sacramental system.

227
00:30:54,200 --> 00:31:01,200
 But I think if we trust in those spiritual benefits, along the way, we get a lot of just basic human benefits.

228
00:31:01,200 --> 00:31:21,200
 We start to see that as great and reliable as that robot is, is lacking that empathy, that sympathy, that compassion, that real care and concern that I can find in the weak, in the frail, in the limited brother and sister that I encounter when I go to receive that spiritual grace.

229
00:31:21,200 --> 00:31:30,200
 So I think sometimes when we pursue that unique encounter with God along the way, our human interactions are actually enriched.

230
00:31:30,200 --> 00:31:39,200
 And we're going to see their faults and failings, but there's something beautiful about knowing that they bear with our faults and failings.

231
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:53,200
 They support us in our faults and failings because of a real concern and care for us, and not simply because they're programmed to give a certain response that flatters us or builds us up or taps into our psychological vulnerabilities.

232
00:31:53,200 --> 00:31:54,200
 Beautiful.

233
00:31:54,200 --> 00:31:55,200
 Well, Father, thank you so much.

234
00:31:55,200 --> 00:31:56,200
 Well, Father, thank you so much.

235
00:31:56,200 --> 00:31:59,200
 I could spend an eternity speaking with you.

236
00:31:59,200 --> 00:32:13,200
 And to all of you who might have questions, who want to go deeper into your faith or your understanding the history of the church or getting context or even, you know, the readings of the day, we invite you all to use Magisterium AI, the number one Catholic answer engine in the world.

237
00:32:13,200 --> 00:32:15,200
 And that's it for the Catholic Futurist.

238
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:18,200
 My name is Benjamin Crockett, and I'll see you soon.

